ce:section.ce:para:
The successful creation of highly luminous N-CQDs through hydrothermal carbonization is validated by the initial transformation of the precursor solution's colour from transparent to dark brown after the hydrothermal synthesis [12,13]. The morphology, crystallinity, and elemental composition analysis of the synthesized N-CQDs were visualized by SEM, TEM, HRTEM, SAED, and elemental mapping (Fig. 1
                        ). The TEM image of N-CQDs (Fig. 1
                        a) reveals that the synthesized N-CQDs is spherical. As seen in Fig. 1
                        b, we noticed fringes for a single quantum dot at greater magnification, so it is apparent that the N-CQDs consist of sp2 hybridized highly crystalline core. In addition, the graphitic lattice's interlayer spacing of (100) face corresponds to a lattice parameter of ∼ 0.32 nm [14]. Additionally, the N-CQDs selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern in Fig. 1c revealed d-spacing of 0.144 and 0.214 nm. The (110) and (101) planes of the graphitic carbon material can be attributed to these d spacing [15]. The formed product is highly ordered graphitic carbon quantum dots, according to the HRTEM pictures and SAED pattern [15]. From Fig. 1
                        d, we noticed that the size distribution of N-CQDs was between 3 and 6 nm. The hydrodynamic size of synthesized N-CQDs obtained from dynamic light scattering (DLS) measurement was ∼ 15.0 nm (
                           Fig. S1
                        ), which was slightly larger than the size obtained from TEM analysis; this was due to the DLS size is the hydrodynamic size of the N-CQDs [16]. The elementary mapping of N-CQDs is taken over a broad area to get a better result. All the elements, i.e., C, O, and N, are relatively consistently distributed throughout the entire region of N-CQDs, according to SEM-EDX elemental mapping (Shown in 
                           Fig. S2
                        ).
